"/> Often the dealer will subtract the factory to buyer rebate from the
purchase price, and have you sign the form that lets the manufacturer
give the factory to buyer rebate directly to the dealer. Of course this
needs to be made perfectly clear during the negotiations, and in your
case it sounds like it wasn't. When dealers advertise in the newspaper,
they usually will show the final price that includes the factory to
buyer incentives built in.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Any suggestions on how to get the best deal with poor negotiating

"/> skills?

Look at prices on carsdirect.com. If no prices show up for your zip
code, try a zip code of a major metropolitan area near you. Last car I
bought (a Toyota), carsdirect.com was _far_ below the prices I was
getting at nearly every dealer. Most of the dealers were trying to add
on the bogus &quot;advertising fee,&quot; which was kind of funny since Toyota
had just gotten in a load of trouble for doing this. Just when I was
about to buy via carsdirect.com, one dealer had an &quot;all at this price&quot;
sale on the exact vehicle I wanted, and they were about $150 below the
carsdirect.com price. No attempt to add the bogus &quot;advertising fee&quot;
either. Carsdirect offered to match the dealer's price, but their
dealer didn't have the vehicle in stock, so I declined. I've heard some
negatives about actually purchasing via carsdirect.com, such as added
fees such as &quot;delivery fee&quot; and &quot;documentation fee.&quot;

Don't Negotiate Down from MSRP, or Up from Invoice
---------------------------------------------------------
Never bargain down from MSRP, or up from invoice (this is what the
dealers want you to do). Remember, &quot;invoice&quot; is _not_ the same as
dealer cost. Try to find the dealer cost, and make that your baseline.
It's often very difficult to find out what factory to dealer incentives
are in place (and they often vary by region); without knowing these,
you will never know the true dealer cost of the vehicle. There is no
single source to find out factory to dealer incentives. If you see an
&quot;all at this price&quot; sale (as opposed to &quot;one at this price,&quot;) and the
price is _way_ below invoice (as opposed to just a few hundred below
invoice), you can safely assume that there are factory to dealer
incentives in place. On unpopular models, the factory to dealer
incentives can be very high, sometimes more than $10,000 on unpopular
luxury cars that are way overpriced to begin with.

You should be able to get any &quot;normal&quot; vehicle for around 5% over
dealer cost (which ends up right around invoice, unless there are other
incentives). &quot;Normal&quot; means a vehicle that is not in very short supply,
i.e. Honda Odyssey, or the fad vehicle of the year (New Beetle, PT
Cruiser, Miata, etc.). If a dealer is advertising &quot;below invoice&quot; then
you know that their are factory to dealer incentives in place.

For example, look at carsdirect.com for a 2005 Camry LE, one of the
most popular U.S. passenger cars. In southern California, it sells for
$1600 under invoice ($1000 of which is a factory to customer rebate).
So there is probably a factory to dealer incentive in place, since even
when you calculate what the distributor pays in holdback, advertising
fee, and WFR, these amount to only another $900, only $300 over dealer
cost, which no dealer would accept (and they have to pay carsdirect.com
something too). Local dealers are even less for this model, some at
just under $16,000, so there must be at least a $500 factory to dealer
incentive in place.

Ad Fees
---------
Do not believe what Edmund's states about ad fees. Ad fees are an
attempt by the dealer to charge the customer for money the dealer pays
into cooperative advertising funds. The manufacturer subsidizes
advertising, with a per vehicle rebate to the dealer. Of course the
dealer is free to charge whatever they can get for a vehicle, and of
course they have to build _all_ of their costs into that price, but
they can't add on bogus fees and try to make them appear as
non-negotiable line items on the contract. The &quot;ad fee&quot; and &quot;doc fee&quot;
should not even be a concern, since whatever they add, you simply
deduct beforehand, and just let them add them back if they want. The
only legitimate &quot;fee&quot; is the destination charge, which is
non-negotiable.

Buying Services
----------------
There are some buying services offered by places like Costco and Sam's
Club, but I have found these prices to always be higher than
carsdirect.com. The only one that actually appears to be any good is
http://checkbook.org/auto/carbarg.cfm  but it isn't free (see the
testimonials at  http://checkbook.org/auto/cb-press.cfm ).

So the bottom line is that you should a) check carsdirect.com, and
perhaps consider the $190 for  http://checkbook.org/auto/carbarg.cfm  .

Lately, I've preferred waiting for &quot;all in stock at this price&quot; sales,
though I had a dealer try to renege on a deal when it was clear that we
weren't financing, buying an extended warranty, fabric guard,
undercoating, window etching, gold package, or any of the crap they try
to sell you in the finance office.

