incredible deal because they got the car for only a couple of hundred
over invoice, or at invoice. Sometimes there will be some story about
how it was the end-of-the-month, or the dealer was closing for the
night, or the Super Bowl was about to start, etc. Dealers encourage
these beliefs.

In my area, the invoice has become the de-factor retail price from which
to bargain down from, for buyers that do even just a tiny bit of
planning. If you do any research at all, you'll find that what you
really want to do is to find out the dealer cost, and base your offers
on that, rather than bargaining up or down from invoice.

I prepare a spreadsheet with MSRP, Invoice, Dealer Cost, all rebates,
incentives, etc., and based on the dealer cost, come up with a range of
what I'd pay (generally 2%-5% over the true dealer cost, which has
always been below invoice). But you NEVER go into the dealer with any
spreadsheets or printouts from the web, this makes you into an
attractive target for the ad fee, doc fee, or prep fee scams.

&gt; Dealers get other kick-backs, incentives, and items of value from

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
